\par A creature must be willing to be }{\cs27\fs20 levitated}{\fs20 , and an object must be unattended or possessed by a willing creature. The
 caster can mentally direct the subject to move up or down as much as 20 feet each round; doing so is a move-equivalent action. The caster cannot move the recipient horizontally, but the subject could push or pull his or her way provided there is a surfac
e to grasp (generally at half its base speed).
\par A levitating creature that attacks with a melee or ranged weapon finds itself increasingly unstable; the first attack is made with a \endash 1 penalty, the second \endash 2, and so on, up to a maximum penalty of \endash 5. A full r
ound spent stabilizing allows the creature to begin again at \endash 1.
\par 
